1: Removing waves from the gravity current PIV data

1.1: Editorial

The work for this chapter is completely done. I need to extend and refine the words below but the bulk of it is there. I'd estimate a further couple of drafts to finish this off, each taking a day.

The work here is me solving the biggest blocking problem in getting to analyse the rest of the data. As you'll see, the waves in the data were very obvious in any frequency analysis.

Each time I thought I had the problem solved I came across some additional feature of the waves that I hadn't accounted for. This happened for each of

  • the shallow water approximation not holding
  • the horizontal variation of standing waves
  • the vertical profile varying strongly with frequency
  • the waves decaying with time

Realising the waves were not a PIV processing artefact and were standing waves (and therefore controllable) was frustrating. This problem was likely avoidable experimentally and demonstrates nicely what can happen when performing lab work under excess time pressure.

All runs are contaminated with background waves. We can remove high frequency waves from all runs; however, lower frequency waves can only be removed from runs with a long measurement period prior to the front passage. Not knowing this, when doing the experiments I cut down the majority of the runs to include only a short period before the front passage (to save disk space). This leaves us with 5 runs that can be wave-subtracted :(

1.2: Overview

As discussed previously, we are going to look at our gravity current velocity data in a frame of reference moving with the current front (the GC frame).

All velocity data is transformed from the LAB frame into the GC frame, in which the position of the gravity current front is stationary. In the GC coordinate system (z, t, t') we can easily compute a mean current field, along a single axis.

Figure 1 shows the mean of the data in the GC frame. This mean looks as we might expect - like a gravity current in cross section, with a raised head followed by shear induced billows.

The waves are present throughout the time series and well before the front passage.

If we can isolate the wave signal then, assuming superposition, we can recover the waveless signal.

There are several wave frequencies represented: there apears to be a harmonic series beginning at ~0.1Hz, along with a cluster of frequencies around 1Hz.

We will focus now on the harmonic series of frequencies that appears in the power spectrum.

One hypothesis for the cause of the frequency peaks is standing waves in the tank. These could emerge from a number of sources.

The tank is filled with a hose at one end of the tank. In the single layer runs examined here this is done at high speed. The overpressure at the hose inlet would be a sufficient perturbation to excite a series of standing waves.

Another potential source of the waves is the lock release itself; in a tank with a free surface we expect a surface wave mode [@baines1995].

Since we did not control for the source of the waves (e.g with baffles, filling the tank very slowly) we cannot be sure of the source of them but we will focus here on the assumption that they are standing waves.

The phase velocity of linear waves in shallow water \(c_p\) is given by

\[ c_p = \sqrt{gH} \]

The frequencies of standing waves are given by

\[ f_n = \frac{n c_p}{2L} \]

for integer \(n\) (as the waves must have nodes at the ends of the tank due to the \(u=0\) boundary condition.

The full length of the tank is \(L = 5.50 \pm{0.005} \mathrm{m}\) and the height \(H = 0.25 \pm{0.005} \mathrm{m}\), giving a base standing wave frequency of \(f_1 = 0.142 \pm{0.001} \mathrm{Hz}\).

f1 = 0.142
shallow_frequencies = f1 * np.arange(1, 4)

def plot_shallow_frequencies(f1=f1, n=4):
    for n in range(1, n + 1):
        plt.axvline(n * f1, color='k')

fmin = 1 / (r.T[:].max() - r.T[:].min())
fmax = 0.5 / r.dt

1.2.0.1: Frequency resolution in the power spectrum

We can increase the quality of our power spectrum, at least for the harmonic series, by increasing the frequency resolution and by using a more appropriate windowing function on our signal.

Padding the signal with several times its length of zeros will increase the frequency resolution.

An appropriate windowing function will minimise spectral leakage from the frequency components that make up the signal.

We have implicitly used a uniform rectangular (boxcar) window, which has a non monotonic (sinc) frequency representation, leading to spurious peaks to the sides of real ones. A more appropriate choice would be a Hanning window, which has smoothly decreasing side lobes in frequency.

Our improved power spectrum is shown in @fig:extended-power.

## fig:extended-power-shallow
# Windowed and extended power spectrum of streamwise velocity
# prior to front passage. Shallow water standing wave frequencies
# for n < 5 are overlaid.
##

def plot_smooth_fft(signal, **kwargs):
    window = kwargs.pop('window', 'hanning')
    size = kwargs.pop('size', 2**15)
    xlim = kwargs.pop('xlim', (0.05, 2.5))
    ylim = kwargs.pop('ylim', (0, 5))
    ax = kwargs.pop('ax', None) or plt.gca()
    
    window = sig.get_window(window, signal.size, fftbins=False)
    
    fft = np.fft.rfft(signal * window, size)
    freqs = np.fft.rfftfreq(size, d=0.01)
    power = np.abs(fft)
    
    ax.semilogx(freqs, power, **kwargs)

    ax.set_xlim(*xlim)
    ax.set_ylim(*ylim)


plot_smooth_fft(presignal)
plot_shallow_frequencies()
plt.title('power spectrum (windowed and extended)')
plt.xlabel('frequency')
plt.ylabel('power');

1.3: Problem Characterisation

1.3.1: Frequency agreement

Figure 4 shows close agreement between the predicted standing wave frequencies and the observed peaks, however there is an increasing discrepancy at higher frequencies. The cause of this discrepancy is the diminishing validity of the shallow water approximation.

The full dispersion relation for two dimensional water waves is

\[ w^2 = g k \tanh(k H) \]

and the condition for standing waves is given by

\[ k = \frac{2\pi}{\lambda} = \frac{n \pi}{L} \]

Using this relation we get a much improved match between the observed and predicted peak locations, as shown in Figure 5.

## fig:extended-power-standing
# Extended and windowed power spectrum of streamwise velocity.
# Standing wave frequencies using the full dispersion relation
# are overlaid. The full dispersion relation is necessary to find
# the frequencies of higher order standing waves as the shallow
# water approximation loses validity.
##

L = 5.50
H = 0.25
g = 9.81

def kn(n):
    return np.pi * n / L

def standing_frequency(n=None, k=None, scaling=1.006):
    if n is None and k is None:
        return
    elif k is None:
        k = kn(n)
    w2 = g * k * np.tanh(k * H)
    return scaling * np.sqrt(w2) / (2 * np.pi)

def plot_standing_frequencies(n=4, scaling=1.008, color='k', alpha=0.4, **kwargs):
    scaling = kwargs.pop('scaling', 1.008)
    ax = kwargs.pop('ax', None) or plt.gca()
    for i in range(n):
        ax.axvline(standing_frequency(i + 1, scaling=scaling), color=color, alpha=alpha, **kwargs)

plot_smooth_fft(presignal, window='hanning')
plot_standing_frequencies(30)

plt.xscale('linear')
plt.xlim(0.01, 2.5)
plt.ylim(0, 2);

Figure 5 suggests that the vast majority of the observed power in the pre-current signal originates from standing waves.

1.3.2: Resolution of distinct frequency peaks

At higher frequencies it becomes increasingly difficult to resolve the peaks. @harris1978 gives the resolution bandwidth of a single spectral line (using a 6.0dB drop from the peak) for several window functions in @table:window- bandwidth. A pair of equal amplitude peaks must be separated by at least this bandwidth if they are to be resolved. Unequal peaks may require a significantly larger separation.

Resolution bandwidth for several different windowing functions {#table:window-bandwidth}
Window resolution bandwidth (6dB)
Boxcar 1.2
Hamming 1.81
Hanning 1.65
Blackman 2.35

where a bin is \(\omega_s / N\) for the sampling frequency \(\omega_s\) and the number of samples \(N\).

1.3.3: Transition frequency of coherent features

As we can see in @fig-fft-mean-mean, lower frequency features do not average out to have non zero power. We can approximate a frequency below which we expect this to occur as the front speed divided by the observation window width. This approximate transition frequency is shown in Figure 9. At all frequencies, features with constant phase (i.e. standing waves) do not average out to zero power. Incoherent features only average out to zero power at higher frequencies.

def critical_frequency(r):
    """Calculate the frequency below which we expect periodic features
    to not be averaged out by mean subtraction.
    """
    c = r.front_speed
    x = r.X[0, :, 0]
    fcrit = c / (x.max() - x.min())
    return fcrit

fcrit = critical_frequency(r)
def contour_fft(signal, axis=-1, size=2**15, window='hanning', xlim=(0.05, 2.5), levels=(0, 1, 50), ax=None):
    ax = ax or plt.gca()
    window = sig.get_window(window, signal.shape[axis], fftbins=False)
    
    fft = np.fft.rfft(signal * window, size, axis=axis)
    freqs = np.fft.rfftfreq(size, d=0.01)
        
    lvl = np.linspace(*levels)
    x = r.X[0, :, 0]
    Ff, Xf = np.meshgrid(freqs, x)

    which = (freqs > xlim[0]) & (freqs < xlim[1])
    F = Ff[:, which]
    X = Xf[:, which]
     
    return ax.contourf(F, X, np.abs(fft)[:, which], levels=lvl)
    
def plot_total_fft(signal, xlim=(0.01, 3), ylim=(0, 10), window='hanning', size=2**15, ax=None):

    ax.set_xlim(*xlim)
    ax.set_ylim(*ylim)

1.3.4: Removal strategy

As described in Section 1.3.2, it becomes very difficult to identify distinct frequency peaks at higher frequencies.

As described in Section 1.3.3, at lower frequencies we expect there to be features in the current that span the width of the observation window, making it difficult to distinguish standing waves. At higher frequencies, it is more likely that the standing waves will be the only features that are coherent over the width of the window.

Therefore strategy:

  1. Use pre-front signal to identify the first few modes.

  2. Use full signal to identify the remainder of the wavefield, using coherence of the waves to distinguish from remainder.

1.4: Characteristics of standing waves

The horizontal and vertical velocity components due to standing waves with surface amplitude \(\eta\) are given by

\[ u = \frac{\pi \eta_k}{T} \left( \frac{\cosh kz}{\sinh kH} \right) \sin{kx} \sin{\omega_k t} \]

\[ w = \frac{\pi \eta_k}{T} \left( \frac{\sinh kz}{\sinh kH} \right) \cos{kx} \sin{\omega_k t} \]

We can see that the form of standing waves is dependent on the tank geometry, the measurement location, the time since the initial excitation and the projection of the initial excitation onto the possible wave modes.

We will look at each of the horizontal, vertical and time components in turn.

1.4.1: Horizontal variation

The horizontal component of the standing wave velocity components is given by

\[ \label{eq:sw-horizontal-u} u(x) = \sin{kx} \]

\[ \label{eq:sw-horizontal-w} w(x) = \cos{kx} \]

With a non unity reflection coefficient (i.e. in reality) we expect a different form for the horizontal variance of the waves. In particular we do not expect nodes to go to zero.

...Equations with r!=1...

1.4.2: Vertical profile

The vertical profile of the standing wave velocity components is given by

\[ u(z) = \frac{\cosh kz}{\sinh kH} \]

\[ w(z) = \frac{\sinh kz}{\sinh kH} \]

Importantly, these profiles are dependent on the frequency of the standing wave.

def vu(z, k, H=0.25):
    """Vertical profile of horizontal velocity component."""
    return np.cosh(k * z) / np.sinh(k * H)

def vw(z, k, H=0.25):
    """Vertical profile of vertical velocity component."""
    return np.sinh(k * z) / np.sinh(k * H)

def theoretical_vertical_profile(z, k, component='u', norm='max', H=0.25):
    """Compute the vertical profile for given z, k for
    given component of velocity (either 'u' or 'w'), and
    with optional normalisation to the max (default) or 
    mean of the profile or a scalar.
    
    k, z can be scalar or vector
    
    Returns the vertical profile over [z, k]
    """
    k = np.atleast_2d(k)
    z = np.atleast_2d(z).T
    
    if component == 'u':
        v = vu(z, k, H=H)
    elif component == 'w':
        v = vw(z, k, H=H)

    if norm == 'max':
        return v / v.max(axis=0, keepdims=True)
    elif norm == 'mean':
        return v / v.mean(axis=0, keepdims=True)
    elif type(norm) in (float, int):
        return v / norm
    else:
        return v
def create_k_interpolator(with_zero=True):
    """Create a lookup function that finds k as a function of
    frequency."""
    k = np.hstack(([0], np.logspace(-3, 4.5, 100)))
    return interp.interp1d(standing_frequency(k=k), k)

k_f = create_k_interpolator()

def create_vertical_profile(component='u', fmax=20, zmax=0.25, z=None, res=100, norm='max'):
    """For a given velocity component ('u', 'w'), create a function
    that returns the vertical profile of that component for given 
    z, f.
    """
    freqs = np.linspace(0, fmax, res)
    if z is None:
        z = np.linspace(0, zmax, res)

    # Can't actually evaluate vertical profile at f=0,
    # so remove this and tack on the limit (approaching 1 for u)
    profile = theoretical_vertical_profile(z=z, k=k_f(freqs[1:]), component=component, norm=norm)
    
    if component == 'u':
        limit = np.ones(z.size)
    elif component == 'w':
        limit = np.linspace(0, 1, z.size)
    
    profile = np.hstack((limit[:, None], profile))

    return interp.RectBivariateSpline(z, freqs, profile)

uprofile = create_vertical_profile('u', zmax=r.z.max(), norm='max')
wprofile = create_vertical_profile('w', zmax=r.z.max(), norm='max')

Figure 10 shows the transition between the shallow and deep water approximations. In extreme shallow water, the wave occupies the full depth; in extreme deep water, the wave is confined to the surface.

This gives us an a priori idea of the frequency at which standing waves will cease to be a problem throughout the fluid. Below 2Hz, the waves can be said to affect the full fluid depth; above 5Hz, waves are clearly in the deep water regime with energy confined to the surface. Unless the wave forming disturbance has projected a lot of energy onto the higher frequency modes, the higher frequency waves are only going to be visible in the surface layer.

1.4.3: Time decay

Not shown in these equations, but there is dissipation and decay of the wave amplitude.

This decay will be due to a non unity reflection coefficient at the wall and also losses due to viscosity.

In general we expect the time decay to be a function of the fluid viscosity, the standing wave speed and the length of the tank (to account for the number of wall reflections).

1.5: Estimating the waves

1.5.1: Pre-front estimation

Fit successive peaks, minimising power spectrum, allowing for exponential decay and using empirically determined f(x). Could have done this in the time domain, but easier to reason with in the frequency domain.

def find_nearest_idx(array,value):
    return (np.abs(array-value)).argmin()


def find_closest_peaks(power, freqs, guess_freqs):
    """Given a power spectrum over frequencies `freqs` 
    find the array indices of the power spectrum peaks 
    closest to the guess_freqs.
    """
    # find the maxima in the power spectrum
    maxima = sig.argrelextrema(power, np.greater)

    maxima_freqs = np.zeros(freqs.shape)
    maxima_freqs[maxima] = freqs[maxima]
    
    # determine the peaks as the closest maxima to each of the standing wave frequencies
    peak_indices = [find_nearest_idx(maxima_freqs, f) for f in guess_freqs]
    return peak_indices
    

def construct_wave(amplitude, f, time, decay=0):
    return (amplitude * np.exp(2j * np.pi * f * time) * np.exp(decay * time)).real

def wave_fft(amplitude, f, size, window, decay=0, dt=0.01):
    time = np.arange(window.size) * dt
    wave = (2 / window.sum()) * construct_wave(amplitude, f, time, decay=decay) * window
    return np.fft.rfft(wave, size)

def subtract_amplitude_fft(fft, amplitude, f, size, window, decay=0):
    return fft - wave_fft(amplitude, f, size, window, decay=decay)


def minimise_this_decay((amplitude_re, f, amplitude_im, decay), fft, size, window):
    amplitude = np.complex(amplitude_re, amplitude_im)
    return np.linalg.norm(subtract_amplitude_fft(fft, amplitude, f, size, window, decay=decay))


def minimise_power_decay(f, fft, freqs, size, window, bounds=None):
    power = np.abs(fft)
    peak = find_closest_peaks(power, np.array(freqs), guess_freqs=np.array([f]))
    idx = np.abs(freqs - f).argmin()
    
    idx = peak
    
    amplitude = power[idx]
    # get phase from the fft (assume it doesn't change)
    phase = np.angle(fft[idx])
    
    amplitude = fft[idx]
        
    if bounds is not None:
        damp = np.abs(amplitude) * 0.3
        bounds = [(amplitude.real - damp, amplitude.real + damp), 
                  bounds, 
                  (amplitude.imag - damp, amplitude.imag + damp), 
                  (-0.02, -0.002)]
    minim = opt.minimize(minimise_this_decay, 
                         #method='TNC', 
                         x0=(amplitude.real, freqs[peak], amplitude.imag, -0.007), 
                         args=(fft, size, window),
                         bounds=bounds)
                         
    opt_amplitude_re = minim.x[0]
    opt_freq = minim.x[1]
    opt_amplitude_im = minim.x[2]
    opt_decay = minim.x[3]
    
    camplitude = np.complex(opt_amplitude_re, opt_amplitude_im)
        
    return camplitude, opt_freq, opt_decay, wave_fft(camplitude, opt_freq, size, window, opt_decay)


def comb_frequencies_decay(fft, nf, window, size, df=0.01, plots=False):
    freqs = np.fft.rfftfreq(size, d=0.01)
    
    amplitudes = np.zeros(nf, np.complex)
    frequencies = np.zeros(nf, np.float)
    decay = np.zeros(nf, np.float)
    peak_ffts = np.zeros((nf, freqs.size), np.complex)
    
    if plots:
        plt.figure()
        plt.plot(freqs, np.abs(fft), 'k', linewidth=3, alpha=0.5)
    # go through each guess frequency and find the nearest wave 
    # amplitude (complex) and frequency that would minimise the 
    # power spectrum, subtracting the optimal wave each time.
    for i, f in enumerate(standing_frequency(np.arange(1, nf + 1))):
        amplitudes[i], frequencies[i], decay[i], peak_ffts[i] = minimise_power_decay(f, fft, freqs, size, window, 
                                                                                     bounds=(f-df,f+df))
        fft = fft - peak_ffts[i]
        
        if plots:
            plt.plot(freqs, np.abs(peak_ffts[i]))
            plt.plot(frequencies[i], np.abs(amplitudes[i]), 'o')
            plt.annotate(round(decay[i], 4), 
                         xy=(frequencies[i], np.abs(amplitudes[i])), 
                         xytext=(frequencies[i] / (1.2 - 0.05), 1 - 0.1 * (i + 1)),
                         textcoords='axes fraction',
                         arrowprops=dict(facecolor='black', shrink=0.05))
            plt.xlim(0.05, 1.2)
            
    if plots:
        plt.plot(freqs, np.abs(fft))
        
    return amplitudes, frequencies.real, decay, peak_ffts



def extract_waves(data, nf, component='w', size=2**15, window='hanning', 
                  plots=False, length=8000, decay=True, 
                  dct_index=3, vertical=True, z=r.z):
    x = r.X[0, :, 0]
    freqs = np.fft.rfftfreq(size, d=0.01)
    window = sig.get_window(window, data.shape[-1], fftbins=False)
    
    fft = np.fft.rfft(data * window, n=size, axis=-1)
    
    
    amplitudes, frequencies, tdecay, peak_ffts = comb_frequencies_decay(fft.mean(axis=0), nf=nf, window=window, size=size, plots=plots)

    iamp = interp.RectBivariateSpline(x, freqs, np.abs(fft))
    amplitude_variation = iamp(x, frequencies[:nf])
     
    if plots:
        plt.figure()
        plt.plot(x, amplitude_variation, '--')
    
    dct = fftpack.dct(amplitude_variation, axis=0, norm='ortho')
    dct[dct_index:, :] = 0
    amplitude_variation = fftpack.idct(dct, axis=0, norm='ortho')
    
    if plots:
        plt.plot(x, amplitude_variation)
    
    # scale the amplitude variation to its mean
    amplitude_variation /= amplitude_variation.mean(axis=0)
    
    full_amplitudes = amplitude_variation * amplitudes[None, :]

    if not decay:
        tdecay = np.zeros(tdecay.size)
    
    time = np.arange(length) * 0.01
    
    # create waves with axes [z, x, t, k]
    # only varies over [x, t, k] at this point
    waves = (2 / window.sum()) * construct_wave(full_amplitudes[None, :, None, :], 
                                                frequencies[None, None, None, :nf], 
                                                time=time[None, None, :, None],
                                                decay=tdecay[None, None, None, :nf]).real
    
    if vertical:
        # compute vertical profile of computed frequencies 
        # and extend the waves over that profile
        profile = theoretical_vertical_profile(z, k_f(frequencies), norm='mean', component=component)
        return profile[:, None, None, :] * waves
    
    else:
        # remove the empty z axis, returning [x, t, k]
        return waves.squeeze()

1.5.2: Full-signal estimation

Identifying the higher order modes is either very difficult or impossible, due to the limits on peak resolution in the limited pre-front signal (Section 1.3.2).

Here we determine the remainder of the wave field empirically.

1.5.2.1: Variance in x

Real standing waves do not follow the simple theoretical shape given by Equations 1 and 2. The theoretial horizontal profile becomes difficult to estimate with a viscous fluid and non unity reflection at the walls. A data driven technique is needed to determine how the waves vary in the horizontal.

1.5.2.1.1: Data decomposition

We wish to identify features that are coherent over \(x\). We know that the power of any given standing wave will vary in x. We wish to approximate this variance.

Remember, due to the decay of the standing waves over time, we do not know the theoretical form of the variance. Further, the standing waves are superposed on the underlying data that we wish to retrieve.

A first approximation to extracting such features is to take the mean over the x-axis. The result of doing this with our data is shown in @fig:mean-waves(a): subtracting the mean will remove only the invariant part of any standing wave's power.

The mean is the limit of a low pass filter - it is the DC component of the signal. We can better approximate the signal by including non-DC components. Recall that we are relying on the higher frequency standing waves to be the only features in the data that are coherent over x. As we use more higher order coefficients we expect to increasingly include the underlying data in our approximation.

Consider the fourier transform over the x-axis of the horizontal velocity component, as shown in Figure 18(a). The energy representing the standing waves can be seen in the pre-front region. The 1st coefficient, the mean, holds the majority of the energy, with alternate successive coefficients holding the remainder. In the post-front region, the current energy is spread over a wide range of coefficients. This is the problem with the DFT: we cannot separate out the standing wave signal from the current signal because both are spread over a similar range of transform coefficients. A good approximation of the standing waves with the DFT requires that we do not truncate our transform very much; this is a problem because we would very much like to truncate the region in which there is appreciable energy coming from the current.

We can gain a better approximation than the Discrete Fourier Transform by using the Discrete Cosine Transform (DCT). In the DCT, we decompose the signal into a set of cosine modes of the signal length. The crucial difference between the DCT and the DFT is the boundary conditions: periodic for the DFT, but symmetric for the DCT 1. The symmetric boundaries free the DCT to approximate generic signals with far fewer coefficients than the DFT. See Figure 17 for a demonstration of this in the simple case of a ramp: the DFT cannot make a good approximation to this signal because of the constraints on it's boundaries, whereas the DCT can make a good approximation even with only a single non-mean coefficient.

Figure 18(b) shows the DCT as applied to our data. Whereas the DFT in Figure 18(a) spreads energy out over odd coefficients, the standing wave energy is compacted into the first couple of coefficients.

def brickpass(signal, cutoff, high_cutoff=False, axis=-1):
    """Brick wall filter"""
    fft = np.fft.rfft(signal, axis=axis)
    freqs = np.fft.rfftfreq(signal.shape[axis], d=0.01)
    
    s = [slice(None) for _ in range(signal.ndim)]
    s[axis] = freqs < cutoff
    rfft = fft.copy()
    rfft[s] = 0
    
    if high_cutoff:
        s[axis] = freqs > high_cutoff
        rfft[s] = 0
        
    rdata = np.fft.irfft(rfft, axis=axis)
    return rdata

def butterpass(signal, cutoff, high_cutoff=False, axis=-1, order=2):
    """Butterworth filter in frequency domain"""
    fft = np.fft.rfft(signal, axis=axis)
    freqs = np.fft.rfftfreq(signal.shape[axis], d=0.01)
    
    s = [None for _ in range(signal.ndim)]
    s[axis] = slice(None)
    
    n = 2 * order
    
    if cutoff == 0:
        lo_butter = np.ones(freqs.size)
    else:
        lo_butter = 1 - (1 / (1 + (freqs / cutoff) ** n))
        
    if not high_cutoff:
        hi_butter = np.ones(freqs.size)
    else:
        hi_butter = (1 / (1 + (freqs / high_cutoff) ** n))

    rfft = fft * lo_butter[s] * hi_butter[s]
    rdata = np.fft.irfft(rfft, axis=axis)
    return rdata

1.5.2.1.2: Results

Applying the DCT to our data allows us to determine the standing waves and their variance in the x-axis to a good level. Figure 19 shows the results of applying the mean, DFT and DCT methods to our data. Clearly, the DCT is the best performer in subtracting the waves.

def mean_waves(signal, axis=0):
    return signal.mean(axis=axis)

def fft_waves(signal, n=2):
    fft = fftpack.rfft(signal, axis=0)
    fft[n:, :] = 0
    return fftpack.irfft(fft, axis=0)

def dct_waves(signal, n=2, dct_type=2, axis=0, cutoff=0, bandpass=brickpass):
    if cutoff:
        signal = bandpass(signal, cutoff, axis=-1)
    dct = fftpack.dct(signal, axis=axis, type=dct_type, norm='ortho')
    where = [slice(None) for _ in dct.shape]
    where[axis] = slice(n, None)
    dct[where] = 0
    return fftpack.idct(dct, type=dct_type, axis=axis, norm='ortho')

We need to approximate the vertical component. To do so we can use the theoretical profile - it is robust under real conditions, unlike the theoretical horizontal component.

The procedure is this: take the full signal (less the leading waves) and perform the DCT technique above to maximise the standing wave to remainder signal ratio. This gives us a wave signal in (x, t).

Now, transform into the frequency domain and multiply by the theoretical vertical profile to obtain a wave signal in (z, x, f). Transforming back into the time domain gives us a wave signal in (z, x, t).

def get_zxwaves(signal, component='u', cutoff=0.6, bandpass=brickpass, dt=0.01, flo=0.6, fhi=3):
    # create waves that capture the x variance from a mean over z
    xwaves = dct_waves(n=2, signal=signal.mean(axis=0), cutoff=cutoff, bandpass=bandpass)

    # transform to frequency domain
    xfft = np.fft.rfft(xwaves, axis=-1)
    freqs = np.fft.rfftfreq(xwaves.shape[-1], d=dt)

    # indices of frequency limits
    ihi = np.abs(freqs - fhi).argmin()
    ilo = np.abs(freqs - flo).argmin()
    
    # normalise to *mean* of vertical so that we can directly
    # multiply the fft (which comes from a vertical mean)
    vertical_profile = create_vertical_profile(component=component, fmax=20, z=r.z, res=500, norm='mean')
    
    # extend the fft uniformly over vertical
    zxfft = xfft[None, :, :] * np.ones((r.z.size, 1, 1))
    # scale the fft by the theoretical vertical profile, but only 
    # in frequency range that matters (don't want to scale the 
    # non-wave components that form the boundaries of the signal).
    # In principle we should care about the sharp edges here, but
    # it doesn't seem to have a significant effect.
    zxfft[:, :, ilo:ihi] = zxfft[:, :, ilo:ihi] * vertical_profile(r.z, freqs)[:, None, ilo:ihi]  # addresses todo below
        
    # transform back to time domain
    return np.fft.irfft(zxfft, axis=-1)

This process has successfully removed the remaining waves from the signal. All that remains are a ringing artefact and a background, varying over \((x, t)\).

The ringing originates from high-pass filtering the signal that is fed to the DCT procedure. It is necessary to high-pass filter to avoid capturing x-variance that comes from large scale features in the current: we use a high order (n=6) butterworth filter. The scale of the ringing is shown in Figure 25, along with the ringing caused by a brick filter centered at the same frequency. Since the ringing effect is small away from the edges and the interesting part of our data is well centered in the time domain, we shall ignore this effect.

The background field is shown in Figure 29, with the field computed from the data remaining after wave removal and from the pre-removal data. Since these fields differ only by a constant, the background cannot originate from the processing described here. We attribute the background to the initial PIV analysis and subtract it from the data.

def get_waves(run, component='u'):
    preindex = np.s_[..., :3000]
    
    velocity = getattr(r, component.upper())
    
    pre_front = velocity[preindex].mean(axis=0)

    pre_waves = extract_waves(data=pre_front, nf=4, component=component, 
                              window='hanning', plots=True, length=8000).sum(axis=-1)
    
    
    prewaveless = velocity[..., :8000] - pre_waves[..., :8000]
    
    zxwaves = get_zxwaves(prewaveless, component=component, cutoff=0.45, bandpass=partial(butterpass, order=6))
    
    background = (prewaveless - zxwaves)[..., :3000].mean(axis=-1)
    
    return pre_waves + zxwaves + background[..., None]
